{"id":"1912.01886","submitter":"S\\'ebastien Camalet","authors":"S. Camalet","title":"Quantifying nonlocality as a resource for device-independent quantum key\n  distribution","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 102, 012617 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.102.012617","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We introduce, for any bipartite Bell scenario, a measure that quantifies both\nthe amount of nonlocality and the efficiency in device-independent quantum key\ndistribution of a set of measurement outcomes probabilities. It is a proper\nmeasure of nonlocality as it vanishes when this set is Bell local and does not\nincrease under the allowed transformations of the nonlocality resource theory.\nThis device-independent key rate $R$ is defined by optimizing over a class of\nprotocols, to generate the raw keys, in which each legitimate party does not\nuse just one preselected measurement but randomly chooses at each round one\namong all the measurements at its disposal. A common and secret key can\ncertainly be established when $R$ is positive but not when it is zero. For any\ncontinuous proper measure of nonlocality $N$, $R$ is tightly lower bounded by a\nnondecreasing function of $N$ that vanishes when $N$ does. There can thus be a\nthreshold value for the amount of nonlocality as quantified by $N$ above which\na secret key is surely achievable. A readily computable measure with such a\nthreshold exists for two two-outcome measurements per legitimate party.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Dec 2019 10:43:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 14 Mar 2020 09:45:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 26 Nov 2020 08:39:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-11-30"}
